news_text:
2025-04-17 23:51 ET - News Release
Mr. John Cash reports
UR-ENERGY PROVIDES PRODUCTION AND CONSTRUCTION UPDATES FOR 2025 Q1
Ur-Energy Inc. has  provided the following updates for Q1 2025 from Lost Creek and Shirley Basin.
Lost Creek production
During Q1 2025, the company dried and packaged 83,066 pounds and shipped 106,301 pounds U3O8 (triuranium octoxide). At quarter-end, the company's in-process inventory at Lost Creek was approximately 29,700 pounds, its drummed inventory at Lost Creek was 10,772 pounds, and its finished inventory at the conversion facility was 368,540 pounds. Ur-Energy's next shipment of product is scheduled for next week and the company currently has 57 drums of product on the ground at Lost Creek.
Ur-Energy is pleased to report that the well field flow rate has increased by 44 per cent since the beginning of March, 2025, and is now routinely over 2,700 gallons per minute. Additional flow increases are expected throughout the summer as Ur-Energy's current fleet of 19 contract drill rigs and company construction staff bring on additional header houses and enhance flow in existing wells through routine maintenance and improvements. Head grade remains on target and Ur-Energy's annualized production rate over the past week averaged over 400,000 pounds and remains on a positive trend. For context, the company's 2025 delivery commitment to its customers is 440,000 pounds of U3O8 and the repayment of a 250,000-pound-U3O8 loan in the form of physical pounds, although repayment of this loan may be deferred upon agreement with the lender. Ur-Energy  expects production rates to steadily increase throughout the summer.
The recovery rate in the processing plant has reached design levels as management of the elution circuit has improved, resulting in tail grade on the ion exchange columns commonly being less than three milligrams per litre. The elution and precipitation circuits are now functioning as designed. Both filter presses are operational, and Ur-Energy plans to upgrade the auger in each of the presses in early May, which should further improve throughput. Both rotary vacuum dryers are now operating and performing as designed.
Ur-Energy's safety performance has improved over the past several months with no recordable injury or illness incidents occurring in 2025. Implementation of a behavioural-based safety program to pro-actively address and track potential safety issues has resulted in an improved safety culture and has increased employee participation in company safety initiatives.
The recent improvements in performance and safety are attributable to several factors, of which Ur-Energy  believes the most important are growing employee skills and confidence and achieving higher employee retention rates. The company's increased number of drill rigs, together with mild winter conditions, has also contributed to increased output.
Ur-Energy's objectives for Lost Creek for the remainder of 2025 are to continue to safely ramp up the well field flow rate and improve plant efficiencies by focusing on training, employee retention and improved maintenance.
Shirley Basin construction
Construction at Ur-Energy's fully permitted Shirley Basin project is on target and the company continues to estimate mine start-up by early 2026. Ur-Energy  has hired many of its senior site management and 10 construction staff, who are already directly involved with facility construction. Training of new staff is continuing, including certain training being conducted at Lost Creek. Ur-Energy  has hired several additional professional staff who will join the Shirley Basin team in Q2. Recruiting for operational staff, including remaining managers, will be continuing through the summer.
To date, the following construction activities have been completed:
Upgraded the existing road to an all-weather surface;
Installed and completed approximately 125 monitor wells for Mine Unit 1;
Refurbished the existing warehouse, construction bay and maintenance bay; Ur-Energy originally planned to construct new buildings but saved several million dollars by refurbishing existing buildings;
Installed and furnished modular offices for these buildings;
Installed power between the company's substation and the site for the satellite plant enclosure;
Initiated dirt work for the satellite plant foundation;
Installed communications and security systems;
Installed the septic system for the satellite plant enclosure;
Advanced the construction of the ion exchange vessels, which is well under way in Casper, with delivery expected this fall.
Before Ur-Energy  initiates production at Shirley Basin, the Wyoming Uranium Recovery Program will perform a preoperation inspection. To improve the efficiency of the inspection and operational approvals, Ur-Energy has begun to assemble standard operating procedures and permitting documents for agency review.
In 2025, Ur-Energy  plans to:
Complete the upgrade the company-owned electrical substation;
Install the first header house in Mine Unit 1; two drill rigs were mobilized to the project on April 14 from Lost Creek; Ur-Energy  plans to add four more rigs in Q2; relatively few drill rigs are required for Shirley Basin because dense historic drilling largely diminishes the need for additional exploration or delineation drilling;
Build the relatively small satellite plant enclosure, which will house the ion exchange and waste water management systems;
Construct additional header houses in Ur-Energy's Casper shop;
Install and furnish modular offices for the satellite plant enclosure;
Install two evaporation ponds.
Ur-Energy is excited to bring Shirley Basin, a prolific historic uranium district and the birthplace of in situ uranium mining in 1963, back into production.
Finally, Ur-Energy  wants to briefly mention President Trump's recent executive order that directed the U.S. Department of Commerce to start a national security probe under Section 232 of the Trade Expansion Act of 1962 into the impact of imports of critical minerals and uranium. The investigation is ordered to be completed within 180 days when a final report with recommendations is submitted to the President. The impact of the investigation and subsequent corrective actions, if any, are unknown at this time but could have a positive impact on Ur-Energy as one of the largest domestic uranium producers in the United States.
About Ur-Energy Inc.
Ur-Energy is a uranium mining company operating the Lost Creek in situ recovery uranium facility in southern-central Wyoming. Ur-Energy has produced and packaged approximately 2.9 million pounds U3O8 from Lost Creek since the commencement of operations. Ur-Energy has all major permits and authorizations to begin construction at Shirley Basin, the company's second in situ recovery uranium facility in Wyoming and is advancing Shirley Basin construction and development following the March, 2024, go decision for the mine. Ur-Energy  awaits  the remaining regulatory authorization for the expansion of Lost Creek. Ur-Energy is engaged in uranium mining, recovery and processing activities, including the acquisition, exploration, development and operation of uranium mineral properties in the United States. The primary trading market for Ur-Energy's common shares is on the NYSE American exchange under the symbol URG. Ur-Energy's common shares also trade on the Toronto Stock Exchange under the symbol URE. Ur-Energy's corporate office is in Littleton, Colo., and its registered office is in Ottawa, Ont.
We seek Safe Harbor.
